    {
      "title": "Function discontinuous at a point or inbetween a interval in the given limits",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>The Integral of a Discontinuous function</h3><p>A function $\\text{f}\\left( \\text{x} \\right)$ is defined and continuous when $\\text{a}\\le \\text{x}&lt;\\text{c}$, and either not defined or discontinuous when $x=c$. In this case, one cannot speak of the integral $\\int _{a}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx$ as the limit of integral sums, because $f\\left( x \\right)$ is not continuous on the interval [a,c], and for this reason the limit may not exist.</p><p>The integral $\\int _{a}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx$ of the function $f\\left( x \\right)$ discontinuous at the point $c$ is defined as follows :</p><p>$\\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx=\\underset{b\\to c-0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{b}f\\left( x \\right)dx$</p><p>If the limit on the right exist, the integral is called an important convergent integral, otherwise it is divergent.</p><p>If the function $f\\left( x \\right)$ is discontinuous at the left extremity of the interval [a,c] (that is, for $x=a)$, then by definition $\\int _{a}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{b\\to a+0}}\\int _{b}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx$</p><p>if the function $f\\left( x \\right)$ is discontinuous at some point $x={{x}_{0}}$ inside the interval [a,c], we put</p><p>$\\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx=\\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{{{x}_{0}}}f\\left( x \\right)dx+\\mathop{\\int }_{{{x}_{0}}}^{c}f\\left( x \\right)dx$</p><p>if both improper integral on the right side of the equation exist.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) $\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (a) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ Evaluate }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\int _{0}^{1}\\frac{dx}{\\sqrt{1-x}}\\cdot &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (b) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ Evaluate }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ the }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ integral }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\int _{-1}^{1}\\frac{dx}{{{x}^{2}}} \\\\ &nbsp;\\end{array}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><ol><li>$\\int _{0}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{\\sqrt{1-\\text{x}}}=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{b}\\to 1-0}}\\int _{0}^{\\text{b}}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{\\sqrt{1-\\text{x}}}=-\\left. \\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{b}\\to 1-0}}2\\sqrt{1-\\text{x}} \\right|_{0}^{\\text{b}}$</li></ol><p>$=-\\underset{\\text{b}\\to 1-0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,2\\left( \\sqrt{1-\\text{b}}-1 \\right)=2$</p><ol><li>Since inside the interval of integration there exists a point $\\text{x}=0$ where the integral is discontinuous, the internal must be represented sum of two terms :</li></ol><p>$\\mathop{\\int }_{-1}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}=\\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}\\to -0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\mathop{\\int }_{-1}^{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}+\\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{2}}\\to +0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\mathop{\\int }_{{{\\varepsilon }_{2}}}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}$</p><p>Calculate each limit separately :</p><p>$\\underset{a\\to -0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\mathop{\\int }_{-1}^{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}}\\frac{dx}{{{x}^{2}}}=-\\left. \\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}\\to -0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\frac{1}{x} \\right|_{-1}^{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}}=-\\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}\\to -0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\left( \\frac{1}{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}}-\\frac{1}{-1} \\right)=\\infty $</p><p>Thus, the integral diverges on the interval $\\left[ -1,0 \\right]$</p><p>$\\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}\\to +0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\mathop{\\int }_{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}=-\\underset{{{\\varepsilon }_{1}}\\to +0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\left( 1-\\frac{1}{{{\\varepsilon }_{2}}} \\right)=\\infty $</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"293\" height=\"265\">&nbsp;</p><p>And this means that the integral also diverges on the interval $\\left[ 0,1 \\right]$. Hence, the given integral diverges on the entire interval $\\left[ -1,1 \\right]$. It should be noted that if we had begun to evaluate the given integral without paying attention to the discontinuity of the integrand at the point $\\text{x}=0$, the result would have been wrong.</p><p>Indeed $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\int _{-1}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}=-\\left. \\frac{1}{\\text{x}} \\right|_{-1}^{1}=-\\left( \\frac{1}{1}-\\frac{1}{-1} \\right)=-2$</p><p>which is impossible (fig.)</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd3ec03b9dcaf1afe9fa"
    },
    {
      "title": "When the limits are not finite",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Improper Integral</strong></h3><p>If $f\\left( x \\right)$ is continuous on $\\left[ a,\\infty \\right]$, then $\\int _{a}^{\\infty }f\\left( x \\right)dx$ is called as improper integral and</p><p>\\(\\int_a^{\\infty} f(x) d x=\\lim _{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\int_a^b f(x) d x\\)</p><p>If the Right Hand Limit of integral exists then the improper integral is convergent otherwise it is divergent.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd41c03b9dcaf1afea09"
    },
    {
      "title": "Problems in which Definite Integration can be solved by Substitution",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Problems in which integral can be found by Substitution method</h3><p><strong>Working Rule :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>When definite integral is to be found by substitution then change the lower and upper limits of integration. If substitution is $\\text{z}=\\phi \\left( \\text{x} \\right)$ and lower limit of integration is a and upper limit is $\\text{b}$ then new lower and upper limits will be $\\phi \\left( a \\right)$ and $\\phi \\left( b \\right)$ respectively.</p><p><strong>Q) Find the value of \\(\\int_0^{~~\\frac{\\pi}{2}} \\frac{\\cos x}{(1+\\sin x)^2} d x\\)</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $\\text{z}=1+\\text{sinx}$, then $\\text{dz}=\\text{cosx}d\\text{x}$</p><p>When $\\text{x}=0,\\text{z}=1+\\text{sin}0=1+0=1$</p><p>and when $\\text{x}=\\frac{\\pi }{2},\\text{z}=1+\\text{sin}\\frac{\\pi }{2}=1+1=2$</p><p>Now $I=\\int _{0}^{~~\\frac{\\pi }{2}}\\frac{\\text{cos}x}{{{(1+\\text{sin}x)}^{2}}}dx=\\int _{1}^{2}\\frac{dx}{{{z}^{2}}}=\\int _{1}^{2}{{z}^{-2}}dz$</p><p>$=\\left[ \\frac{{{\\text{z}}^{-1}}}{-1} \\right]_{1}^{2}=-\\left[ \\frac{1}{\\text{z}} \\right]_{1}^{2}=-\\left[ \\frac{1}{2}-1 \\right]=\\frac{1}{2}$</p><p><strong>Note : </strong>Only principal value of $\\theta $ is taken. For example when $\\text{sin}\\theta =0,\\theta =n\\pi $ but principal value of $\\theta $ is 0 .</p>",
      "position": 3,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd43c03b9dcaf1afea14"
    }
